issue.title: In some circumstances, building and creating referenced documents fails
issue.body:
I have a `TeamMember` class:

```ruby
class TeamMember
  include Mongoid::Document

  field :name, type: String
  
  has_and_belongs_to_many :teams
end
```
and a `Team` class:

```ruby
class Team
  include Mongoid::Document
  
  has_and_belongs_to_many :team_members
  
  def member_names=(names)
    names.split(/\s*,\s*/).each do |name|
      team_member = TeamMember.first(conditions: {name: name})
      if team_member
        self.team_members << team_member
      else
        self.team_members.build(name: name)
      end
    end
  end
end
```

As it can be seen, I am passing a string of comma separated names to the `Team`'s `create!` method using a virtual attribute to create or assign its team members:

```ruby
Team.create(member_names: "member1, member2")
```


However when the team member does not exit, and the control flow enters:

```ruby
else
  self.team_members.build(name: name)
end
```

An exception is thrown:

```
You have a nil object when you didn't expect it!
You might have expected an instance of Array.
The error occurred while evaluating nil.push
```

A similar process works with both of MongoMapper and ActiveRecord. It would be nice if Mongoid could handle this scenario as well. I think at the moment Mongoid cannot create referenced documents from a call to `create!`.

I am using Mongoid 2.3.4 and Rails 3.1.3.

issue.title: Standardization Across Examples
issue.body:
There is some standardization that needs to happen across the examples.  For instance, some of them store things between refresh and other don't.  Some have a "mark all" checkbox and some don't.  These are fairly straightforward to implement in each of the versions where it's missing, and I've started on this.

Another piece of this that I'm coming across is the third party libraries used by some of these.  I think we should try to figure out a way to standardize which third party plugins should be used.  One example that I think should be removed is things like emberjs using Sassy CSS (scss).  SCSS is interesting and good to use, but I don't think it contributes to the nature of this project.  If it's decided that SCSS is so valuable, then we should be using it on all of the projects and not just one.  Another one of these is javascriptmvc's use of StealJS.  I know that they work together, but it would be great if we weren't using compiled production code for the demo app, and if we could eliminate this from the example completely I think it would help level the playing field between the examples in understandability and size.

I really want some discussion around this and how other people think this should move forward.

comment.body:
All valid points. One of the largest problems we've had is that there's never been a set of specifications written defining exactly what is expected of a 'Todo' application. This has led to some of the applications being written with basic list/add/remove/edit capabilities, but there's little else provided in terms of guidance other than saying 'study one of the other apps and base it off of that'. The obvious problem there is certain visual specs (mark all checkbox etc.) have been omitted in some implementations whilst not in others.

I agree about us dropping ember's SCSS. Another problem I ran into was trying to decide whether to continue opting for what the official solution was advocating for use (eg. Ember's original todo app that I refactored used SCSS so I assumed developers using it would wish to go for it too), however in hindsight, everything should just be using simple stylesheets instead. 

What I see as us needing to do to clean the examples up is:

* Define what is expected of a typical application
* Identify the apps missing any aspects of these specs
* Working on patching the above

Another intention I had had (but never had time for) was creating a basic boilerplate (index/CSS) for a Todo app that could be handed to a framework author or someone working with the framework if they wished to create a 'TodoMVC' compatible example for submission. This is another area where those submitting pull requests for their own frameworks have run into trouble and whilst it may not be directly solved by our cleanup, it's worth keeping in mind.

commits.message: Root changes

Fix use of filter symmetry in add_glare

The previous attempt to use filter x-y symmetry to speed up
calculation of the filter matrix didn't work correctly for non-square
images.

This change fixes that problem, and also uses vertical and horizontal
symmetry to further reduce the amount of calculation done.

A somewhat subtle change is that the filter is now truly symmetric,
rather than being shifted by 0.5 pixels in x and y directions.

So the value at location 0,0 in the filter matrix represents only the
positive quadrant, with the filter center at the origin (whereas
previously it represented all four quadrants around the filter origin,
with half the extent in each direction).

issue.title: MSIE User-Agent detected as RealPlayer
issue.body:
Why does HTTP::BrowserDetect think that these User-Agents are RealPlayer?

"Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 6.1; Trident/4.0; (R1 1.6); SLCC2; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET CLR 3.0.30729; Media Center PC 6.0; InfoPath.2)"
"Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 5.1; Trident/4.0; GTB7.2; (R1 1.6); .NET4.0C; .NET CLR 1.1.4322; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.0.4506.2152; .NET CLR 3.5.30729)"
"Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 6.0; Windows NT 5.1; SV1; BTRS122155; EasyBits GO v1.0; (R1 1.6); .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.0.04506.648; .NET CLR 3.5.21022; .NET CLR 3.0.4506.2152; .NET CLR 3.5.30729)"

I am using the most recent version (1.39). Here is an example:

% perl -MHTTP::BrowserDetect -le 'print $HTTP::BrowserDetect::VERSION; print HTTP::BrowserDetect->new("Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 6.1; Trident/4.0; (R1 1.6); SLCC2; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET CLR 3.0.30729; Media Center PC 6.0; InfoPath.2)")->browser_string'
1.39
RealPlayer

comment.body:
That sounds like a good idea.  If R1 merely indicates that RealPlayer is installed, we shouldn't return RealPlayer as the browser string unless we can say with confidence that that's the case.  There's maybe an argument to be made that ->realplayer could return true even if the browser string indicates MSIE, but there's no precedent for that elsewhere in the module.  So I think that would be more weird and confusing than anything else.

That second example has a decent version number.  In the first case, I guess we return undef for the version number?

Other than the address bar (unless your mobile OS hid it automatically), there is no way to tell which version of the jQuery Mobile documentation you're viewing. Seems like there's a decent chance people are unknowingly landing on previous versions of the docs after a Google search.

Adding that wouldn't fix the problem with previous versions of the docs, but I don't know how big of an issue that really is. I was playing around with something that could be added  to the jqm-docs/js file, but I just ended up with a Chrome userscript that notifies you if you're on an old version. issue.body:
For the next release, improving page transitions is a top priority. It's clear that overlfow: support isn't broadly supported and that JS scrollers are heavy and only work on a small slice of our target platforms so we need to make sure that we have a solid set fo baseline transitions that work on the greatest number of platforms and are as smooth and blink-free as possible.

- need a re-think to embrace the constraints we have 
- scrolling the docs can't be avoided, but we can hide the jumpiness = introduce 1-2 new transitions that are smooth on all our platforms and work within the performance realities and constraints we have 
- video sketch for animations (slow to illustrate the steps) - http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=di3-fz5TZKQ
- consider packing the new transitions with the switch from keyframe-based animations to transitions so we can package these with Opera, Firefox and IE10 support
- speed up page load/enhancement/transition time overall

issue.title: 2 second delay parsing multipart/form-data
issue.body:
Note: I'm fairly sure this is a Werkzeug issue, and not a Flask or CURL issue, but I could be wrong. I'm guessing it has to do with byte counting and socket timeouts... I have a very small Flask application that looks like the following: ```python from flask import Flask, request app = Flask(__name__) @app.route('/test', methods=['GET', 'POST']) def test(): return '
%r
' % (request.form,) if __name__ == '__main__': app.run(port=5555) ``` If I run the server and then issue two very similar cURL commands against it, I get wildly different response times: tony@quaternion ~/Projects/test/test# time curl -d 'foo=bar' http://localhost:5555/test 127.0.0.1 - - [03/Nov/2011 12:06:15] "POST /test HTTP/1.1" 200 - 
ImmutableMultiDict([('foo', u'bar')])
real 0m0.009s user 0m0.003s sys 0m0.003s tony@quaternion ~/Projects/test/test# time curl -F 'foo=bar' http://localhost:5555/test 127.0.0.1 - - [03/Nov/2011 12:06:22] "POST /test HTTP/1.1" 200 - 
ImmutableMultiDict([('foo', u'bar')])
real 0m2.009s user 0m0.003s sys 0m0.003s tony@quaternion ~/Projects/test/test# The only difference between the two commands (as far as I know...) is that with -d, the data is sent URL-encoded, whereas with -F it's sent as multipart/form-data. I went ahead and ran a trace on it, and what I'm seeing is this: --- modulename: formparser, funcname: _find_terminator 13.09 formparser.py(303): for line in iterator: --- modulename: wsgi, funcname: make_line_iter 13.09 wsgi.py(606): stream = make_limited_stream(stream, limit) --- modulename: wsgi, funcname: make_limited_stream 13.09 wsgi.py(577): if not isinstance(stream, LimitedStream): 13.09 wsgi.py(581): return stream 13.09 wsgi.py(607): _read = stream.read 13.09 wsgi.py(608): buffer = [] 13.09 wsgi.py(609): while 1: 13.09 wsgi.py(610): if len(buffer) > 1: 13.09 wsgi.py(617): chunks = _read(buffer_size).splitlines(True) --- modulename: wsgi, funcname: read 13.09 wsgi.py(773): if self._pos >= self.limit: 13.09 wsgi.py(775): if size is None or size == -1: # -1 is for consistence with file 13.09 wsgi.py(777): to_read = min(self.limit - self._pos, size) 13.09 wsgi.py(778): try: 13.09 wsgi.py(779): read = self._read(to_read) --- modulename: socket, funcname: read 13.09 socket.py(340): rbufsize = max(self._rbufsize, self.default_bufsize) 13.09 socket.py(344): buf = self._rbuf 13.09 socket.py(345): buf.seek(0, 2) # seek end 13.09 socket.py(346): if size < 0: 13.09 socket.py(362): buf_len = buf.tell() 13.09 socket.py(363): if buf_len >= size: 13.09 socket.py(371): self._rbuf = StringIO() # reset _rbuf. we consume it via buf. 13.09 socket.py(372): while True: 13.09 socket.py(373): left = size - buf_len 13.09 socket.py(379): try: 13.09 socket.py(380): data = self._sock.recv(left) 14.74 socket.py(385): if not data: 14.74 socket.py(387): n = len(data) 14.74 socket.py(388): if n == size and not buf_len: 14.74 socket.py(394): return data Notice the ~2 second delay between socket.py lines 380/385. Obviously, the socket is blocking. Althought this is not Werkzeug code (at this point), I'm assuming the problem might have to do with the value of `left` or the initial configuration of the socket. Thanks for looking, and keep up the great work on Werkzeug/Flask et. al.

Even though this is incorrect markup, we should put in a check to see if there is duplication between the role and auto-init and not apply the markup enhancements twice in this scenario to make this fool-proof.

issue.title: QuasiQuotes for hmatrix
issue.body:
This pull request implements vec and mat quasiquoters for hmatrix. The syntax follows that of the (currently out-of-date) hmatrix-static. 

 * I realise that supporting quasiquoters would add significant dependencies to hmatrix, namely Template Haskell and haskell-src-exts. If this dependency is too burdensome, then I will instead release the code as a separate package, hmatrix-syntax.

 * This pull request is dependent on https://github.com/benmachine/haskell-src-meta/pull/10 and https://github.com/mboes/th-lift/pull/5

 * Note that we depend on template-haskell-2.7, which comes with GHC 7.4. We do not support earlier versions of template haskell, because they do not support "unresolved infix" expressions, which are essential for getting the operator fixities correct in quasiquoters. (This is a somewhat subtle point to explain; see http://hackage.haskell.org/trac/ghc/ticket/4430)

 * I have broken up the code into two commits. The first commit implements the quasiquoters by converting to lists and back; the second commit reimplements the quasiquoters using direct unchecked array accesses, for efficiency.

comment.body: Sounds good - the only reason I had to put the code in hmatrix proper was to have everything in one place. But this isn't a big deal, so I'll go ahead and make the package hmatrix-syntax.

issue.title: Please add cl-conceptual-types
issue.body:
This very trivial library is intended to avoid one fairly systematic source of symbol "duplications" and thus potential symbol conflicts.

Homepage: http://www.hexstreamsoft.com/projects/cl-conceptual-types/

GitHub page: https://github.com/Hexstream/cl-conceptual-types

Quicklisp should pull from http://www.hexstreamsoft.com/projects/cl-conceptual-types/cl-conceptual-types_latest.tar.gz

Thanks.

comment.body:
My vision for the focus of this library has evolved rapidly. I'm thinking of renaming it "incidental-keywords" (package nickname "IKEYWORD"). Really the main point of this library is to allow one to "incidentally" use symbol names that would have traditionally been very clashy, but without the associated mess of symbol conflicts. Sometimes in DSLs you might want to use short, convenient symbol names such as MACRO and whatnot, but this can result in annoying conflicts when you combine libraries. Traditional methods of avoiding this are just using keyword symbols or "mangling" the names in various ways (such as using a "package prefix" as part of the name), but I don't find these approaches particularly convenient.

Due to the instability, I'm temporarily withholding the Quicklisp inclusion request. I'm hoping to sort out things in time for the upcoming Quicklisp dist update.

I'll create a separate inclusion request after the name change.

The solution was not to complicate expressions, but actually just
generalise what we can assign to (!).  Of course, some more skilful
splitting of expr would mean we can actually leave assignments to
unassignables as syntax errors, but this fixes the immediate problem.

For future reference:

The issue was that the more-specific "LABEL" couldn't be reduced yet
(since a funcstmt or assignstmt might use that on its LHS), which means
we could never reduce that to an expr.  Hence "f(x)" would only ever be
interpreted as the start of a funcstmt, and never as a callexpr.

issue.title: Change default network driver
issue.body:
When adding a network driver to a VM the default is the the pcnet driver.

After having some serious performance issues (after prolonged use the guest's interface would grind to a halt) The qemu log file indicated some problem with the pcnet driver.

According to the qemu documentation http://wiki.qemu.org/Documentation/Networking the rtl8139 driver should be the default for qemu-kvm and e1000 should be the default for qemu.

To check my findings I changed one of my vms back to using the pcnet driver and the problem recurred, while the others using the rtl8139 driver remained in good order.

Since the performance issues have since disappeared since following these guidelines, I suggest they should be adopted as the default option within the Archipel client.
